      <bioghist id="ref2">
         <head>Biographical Sketch</head>
         <p>Cornelius Osgood (b. 1905, d. 1983) was Curator of Anthropology at the Yale Peabody Museum from 1934 to 1973. He brought significant collections to the Museum from his research expeditions to the Arctic, China and Korea. Osgood may be best known for his research among the Athapaskan speaking people of interior Alaska, much of it published through the Yale University Publications in Anthropology series, and was also active in Connecticut archaeology.</p>
         <p>Education</p>
         <p>- Ph.B. University of Chicago, 1927</p>
         <p>- Ph.D. University of Chicago, 1930</p>
         <p>Field work</p>
         <p>- Northwest Territory, Canada (1928-1929, 1931, 1932, 1934, 1937)</p>
         <p>- Yunnan, China, began 1938</p>
         <p>- Yale Caribbean Anthropological Program, began in 1933</p>
         <p>--Lake Valencia, Venezuela</p>
         <p>--Chiriqui Province, Panama</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="ref4">
         <head>Description of the Material</head>
         <p>Miscellaneous archives accumulated during Cornelius Osgood's time at the Peabody Museum.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
